            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Okay, my eyes betrayed me for a moment there. It is a bug in Blink. It's responding to the DSR, but incorrectly. When I run\n```bash\nprintf \"\\e[5n\"; cat -v\n```\nI see `^[0n` printed out. That's simply `ESC 0 n`.\nIt should be `^[[0n` (`CSI 0 n`). \nThe `ESC 0` from Blink gets interpreted as Alt (which you can test by running `cat -v` and pressing Alt + 0), so nvim sees Alt + 0, then it sees an n.",
